Some of their models, like the HD25 or the Hd280pro are often used in recording studios, by live audio engineers and also DJ¬¥s!! So you are right to some degree, the the lower priced, wireless and even the very high priced highend hifi models are consumer models, but some of the traditional, not so fancy but good quality, midpriced models are real working horses in the pro audio industry!
beside that, they have some real iconic microphones that are standard when it comes to record instruments. some of these models have their roots back in the 50¬¥s like the md421 and are an important part in what becomes the way we all learned how some instruments sound on recordings since the 60¬¥s.
So what i mean is, if they realy sell the whole headphone sector, that is a big thing for a lot of audio-engineers.
Because as an audio-engineer you need to know what you hear and for that, you need to know how your headphone sounds.
That¬¥s why every engineer brings his own headphones to the job, often you choose your model and stick with it as long as it is build,.
To swap a model is like ....how should i say it....every speaker or headphone model sounds in an unique way, so the goal is to get a result that sounds good on every device, mobile phone to big hifi speakers, in order to get that result, you need know exactly what the headphones do with the material you are hearing.
And that is a complex thing, it¬¥s not simply "my headphones have a lot low frequencies, i know that and have to be carefull not to cut to much bass in my mix..." it is way more, like the wideness of the stereo image, how good does it project rooms, where does it blurr, where does it sound to clear....

So i hope they keep some of these models in the pro-audio portfolio, wth all of the support we are used to.....

Import taxes & tariffs are NOT shipping fees - LTT doesn't have any control over them; they are levied by and go to the government(s) the purchased items are entering.

EXPORT taxes & tariffs are the same thing, just for the government(s) the items are LEAVING.


e.g. Let's say Linus starts selling....*looks around* uh, desks and chairs for gamers/computer users. And let's say due to the much greater industrial capacity, the furniture is made better and cheaper in the USA, despite Linus & LTT being in Canada. Logically, to simplify pre-order transportation of product (and minimize delays in stocking and fulfilling orders), the distributor that works with LTT to buy the American-made chairs & desks is ALSO in the US.

And let's say you live in *closes eyes and clicks on a map* uh, INDIA.

Okay, so now, when you order a gaming chair from LTT, they forward the order from Canada to the US distributor, and they ship the chair from the US to India, and the US gov't might (well, since Daffy Donald, WILL) charge an export tariff on ANY product LEAVING the US, so in addition to the literal costs of paying the shipper to bring the chair to you, they have to charge the tariff, which then goes into the US treasury.

Now, if you happened to be in the US yourself, then import/export tariffs wouldn't apply since the product you're buying never crosses a national border. LTT has no influence on whether the tariff(s) are charged or how they apply regardless of Linus being in Canada, also in the US, or even in *clicks* ....well, that's in the Atlantic Ocean, but it's closest to Morocco, so you see my point anyway! :)

I think the Epic argument about "specialized devices" is nonsense. Did people just forget you can install Linux on PlayStation 3 and PlayStation 4? And you obviously also know you can install Steam on Linux, which means playing "PC games" and using desktop software is not only possible but there are plenty of websites out there explaining how to do it. Consoles are not "specialized devices" and that's a meaningless definition for something that depends purely on business decisions about how to use a product. The SDKs for developing Xbox and Windows games are similar enough that I can easily assume Microsoft could install Windows on Xbox if they wanted to do it, and also Linux. Again, useless argument. If the iPhone is somehow found to be forbidden to have control of software distribution on its platforms, then so must be consoles, which are literally exactly the same. Whether a company decided to make a profit or not on hardware sales changes nothing about this argument and is also purely a business decision...

Coke is made with corn syrup in the USA because it is cheaper than sugar here.  In other countries Coke can get sugar cane from the Caribbean and other places pretty cheaply, but in the USA the government subsidizes sugar beat farmers and places tariffs on imported sugar cane so that the American farmers can make a living.  This raises the price of real sugar to the point where it is more economical for beverage companies to use corn syrup.  (At least this was the case when we talked about it in my economics class a decade or so ago.)

The thing with Sennheiser isn't that they had a hard time modernizing, it's the fact that so many "audiophile" brands exist these days and also at competitive prices or cheaper than what Sennheiser could sell theirs at to compete.. The fact that these days even Planar Magnetic headphones, which even a decade ago cost more than a decent prosumer pair of Sennheisers, you can literally pick up a high quality pair with amazing build quality and amazing sound that give even Sennheiser's high end headphones a run for their money however at the price range of their budget headphones, i.e. Hifiman Sundaras for only <$350, or Planar cans from Thiaudio, Sendy, or some other chinese brand that has great reviews and in the $150-300 price range..

hell, even Electrostatic headphones have come down massively in this past decade.. Such as Hifiman's Jade II electrostatic system which comes with the Electrostatic headphones and the energiser/amp to run them, can be had for ~1200-1500 second hand.. not to mention the price drops on cans by Audeze, their formerly high-end LCD-2s which use to cost $1500+ a decade+ ago, can be had for $800 retail these days, and Audezes typically trash on Sennheiser's sound quality all day long.

Sennheiser simply can not compete anymore unless they massively degrade their build quality and tarnish their reputation in the process. Especially not against the flood of sub $600 Chinese headphones that are built to "audiophile quality/specs" that get praised and positive reviews and compared to the $1000+ audiophile headphone brands. So them selling off their headphone brand to another company that is able and willing to start cutting corners, utilize imported chinese parts, and cut cost, etc, and sennheiser able to point out that they don't actually make them anymore, rather another company, that company is able to do what Sennheiser could not do, while sennheiser can somewhat maintain their reputation in the professional market and also collect licensing fees from the other company for use of their name.

Interestingly enough the sennheiser gaming, office and virtually anything with a mic and Bluetooth was actually not made by sennheiser but by a joint venture called sennheiser communications. The joint venture being with Oticon/Demant another hearing aid company. This company was recently divided into EPOS (gaming + office) (sometimes having the 'powered by sennheiser' appended to it) and the audio and consumer part of it absorbed by Sennheiser. This is purely conjecture, but for the cost model of the air bag vest to work, I'd say that the production and distribution cost of a unit is less than 400, so that they won't go into the red simply because too many are sold but not activated. But the total cost, including R&D, corporate salary etc might be say 600-700 per unit, and that's the actual expected break even point.
And indeed, if they can let a unit go for 400 (in that it won't lose them money) but need 600-700 to reach overall break even, then their current price model would be best for both them and consumers.

Luke's idea of always activate but go after them for more afterwards is also my first though. However, I believe it would need to be much higher than 800. Because I believe if that's an option, most people won't bother pay for the software and would bet on not getting into such accidents. Which means they will pretty much need to collect that 200-300 from those that did activate it. If we say one out of a hundred people end up needing it, they'd need to collect 20-30k from each activation. Ofc, if it's that high, people might not want to take the risk and might actually pay the premium--it's essentially a non-required insurance. Some people bought insurance before it was mandatory after all. Which in turn drops the required amount. The break even might be around 10k. And that's kind of the problem with this proposal, that still seems to be too much. And might very well end up being uncollectable.

Those are, of course, based on the assumption that they are not just outright greedy and do need 600-700 overall. I can't possibly know. But without being able to proving that they just want all the money w/o needing it, we can't even justify an argument to make them sell it for less. So the only alternative proposed business model is making them sell it for a fixed amount that would cover the total cost, which the 800 kind of does so... that's not even a real proposal.

There should absolutely, without question, be no way whatsoever that any safety product like like that vest can be built with any sort of mechanism that prevents it from working based on whether or not you're subscribed. I'm not willing to even entertain any hypothetical "but what if it potentially could save you money if everyone subsi-- blah blah blaah". No. It's fundamentally unethical to make something like that that is produced to protect your life to have the ability to decide to not save your life. Fuck that. Not only is it just straight up evil, it's also bad design. The functionality of the device to not deploy is something that must be added into the base product at some point, which is adding cost and wasting material. And having the functionality to not deploy adds in a possibility (that wouldn't be there otherwise) for that system to fail. What if you do actually pay your bill, or buy it outright, and it still malfunctions and doesn't deploy? Or even not "malfunction" really, maybe you just have a shitty connection, and it never gets the notice from the seller that your bill was paid.

Absolutely fucking despicable. Any company that tries this should be fined into bankruptcy, and their patents stripped so that non-evil companies can use their inventions properly.

Imagine this become the norm, it goes into your new car. You miss your payment this month, maybe you got fired and didn't have the money, or you just forgot because people are imperfect. You get in a head-on collision, and instead of your seatbelts holding you in and your airbag deploying, the car just decides to let you and your kids go flying through the windshield instead. There is no excuse for that kind of tech to exist.
